TI  - Current dilemmas in the management of inflammatory bowel disease.
PG  - 58-61
AB  - Considerable advances have been made in the treatment of inflammatory bowel
      disease (IBD) mainly in that of Crohn's disease, but many questions still remain.
      We need to develop treatments that modify the disease. The use of
      immunomodulation using cytokines and anti-cytokines is an important step to
      achieve this goal. The standard is now the chimeric monoclonal antibody against
      tumour necrosis factor (TNF) in Crohn's disease. These treatments, however, are
      associated with problems of immunogenicity and autoimmunity. Moreover a
      proportion of patients do not respond to treatment and we do not have
      measurements that predict response. The optimal use and the combined treatment
      with immunosuppression are under investigation. The safety of this treatment in
      the long-term is also not established. These costly drugs are not suitable for
      the management of mild to moderate Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis (UC).
      If it turns out that the antigenic drive of the inappropriate immune reaction is 
      in the lumen of the gut changing the gut flora by using probiotics may be the way
      to go.
